column62: Urban Capacity Study
column63:
Charnwood Borough Council has begun work on a new Local Plan which will cover the period 2011 to 2036. The Council wishes to understand the capacity within the urban areas of the Borough for housing development. The Study will be used to inform the new plan, assist in identifying sites and the amount of greenfield land that may be needed to meet the Borough's housing requirements to 2036.
The study should seek to identify opportunities for providing new dwellings on previously developed land and buildings within settlements. The evidence will provide expert advice to:
• understand the development potential for housing within the urban areas;
• assist in ensuring that housing on previously developed land is maximised in sustainable locations; and
• establish whether there will be a need to release greenfield sites to meet the housing requirements in the Borough. 
The consultants should set out a methodology which will provide the intended advice and evidence for this commission and meet the study's objectives. 
Please Note
Last date for request of Quotation Documents is 11/08/2017

column63:
Rother District Council and Wealden District Council are seeking to appoint a suitably qualified and experienced operator for Tourism Information Services to be delivered efficiently across the two districts.
      
      Rother District Council requires a supplier to provide and manage Visitor Information Services across the district. It will include the operation, management and monitoring of 3 Tourist Information Points (TIPs, based in Battle, Bexhill and Rye) and a minimum of 18 Local Information Points (LIPs, of which there are currently 30). The contract will require the supplier to actively promote the 1066 Country campaign and events, attractions, places of interest and facilities across the District. This will also include engaging with local organisations to facilitate the hosting of the TIPs and LIPs.

column62: 000896 RFI Collection Management Solution
column63:
The Library is seeking information to assist the implementation of a Collection Management Solution, to manage the processes of acquiring, describing, preserving and enabling access to our collections. The solution we are seeking must be efficient and extensible, capable of managing the large amounts of complex metadata and content described above, and integrating the various specialist components in a shared collection management and discovery infrastructure via standardised interfaces to internal and external users.
We need to know what technologies and/or services might be suitable, together with indicative costs of the system, its implementation, support and maintenance. The Library is therefore inviting potential vendors to provide information on the potential options available for provision of components of the proposed Collection Management Solution.
We invite vendors responding to this RFI to provide as much information relating to the requirements specified as they see fit, on the understanding that no single system may fulfil all of them.

column23: 4 Axis Milling Station for Active Cells Remote Handling Facility.
column36: Early engagement notice on Contracts Finder
column62: 4 Axis Milling Station for Active Cells Remote Handling Facility.
column63:
The UK Atomic Energy Authority (UKAEA) is a non departmental government body. UKAEA is managing the delivery of the Active Cells remote handling facility as part of the UK contribution to the European Spallation Source (ESS) in Sweden. The purpose of the facility is to process and store spent radiologically activated target station components.
 Work on handling processes and in-cell equipment/facilities are progressing towards the detailed design phase. For individual processes and items of equipment, options need to be identified, assessed against the requirements, and developed towards a suitable design ready for manufacture.
 This market enquiry relates to the 4-Axis Milling Station that will be situated inside the Process Cell (PC). The Milling Station will allow for the recovery and subsequent processing of containers of exotic materials that are contained within 2 of the activated components.
 The Milling Station will be operated remotely without local manual intervention. The use of fluids in the for coolant and in any hydraulic actuation or clamping will not be allowed, although lubrication in gearboxes, etc. is permissible.
 The first component is a sealed 6 000 kg, 2 500 mm diameter stainless steel disk that contains 36 stainless steel cassettes each containing a set of tungsten bricks. Each cassette weighs approximately 100 kg and is designed to be removed radially once the rim of the disk has been machined off.
 The second component is a 3 500 kg steel block approximately 620 mm high, 1 200 mm wide and 1 350 mm long. This block consists of a base plate and 2 top sections that are sealed over the top of a 150 kg container of beryllium by a set of stitch welds. The beryllium container can be removed when the stitch welds have been machined off.
 Optional additional scope would include a robotic handling system that can support cut sections and lift the material containers free of the main components once freed.
 The solution will require design, manufacture and installation into the Active Cells facility. This PIN has been published to enable market research to commence to assess the reaction of the market to the requirement and to review available technologies. UKAEA will conduct a dialogue with the marketplace and this may result in a call for competition based on the scope of the requirement developed through the dialogue.

column63:
Central Bedfordshire Council wishes to invite suitably qualified and experienced providers to express an interest in a framework agreement for the provision of Mechanical and Electrical Engineering Services for an initial period of two years with the possibility of an extension considered on a yearly basis for another two years.
      
      The work will cover Design and Build elements under separate Lots:
      
      Lot 1 - Mechanical Services            Lot 2 - Electrical Services
      
      Design and Build Services - the framework will allow the authority to directly award projects or to call off suppliers on the framework to express an interest to enter a mini competition and tender for works within their Lot(s) 
      
      Building Condition Surveys - the framework will allow the authority to call off suppliers to express an interest to enter a mini competition and tender to carry out Condition Surveys
      
      Collateral warranties for services will be required.
      
      Pricing will be based on The National Schedule of Rates 2016/17 with the Suppliers' required tender adjustments to these published rates.
      
      The framework will commence from Feb 2018  for an initial period of two years.
      
      The annual value of the framework contract is in the region of £1million per annum and is below the OJEU value for works.
      
      Completed Tenders and attachments should be submitted electronically, no later than 12:00 noon on 31/10/2017, tenders received after that time will be excluded.
      Tenders must be uploaded via the \My Return\" section of the system. Tenders submitted through the correspondence facility will not be considered.

column62: SCH - Supply of Furniture to Temporary Accommodation Properties
column63:
Solihull Community Housing (SCH) manages council housing on behalf of Solihull Council. We are one of the leading 'arm's length management organisations' (ALMOs) in the country. 
      
      SCH's responsibilities include the management and maintenance of the Council's housing stock, which includes approximately 92 temporary accommodation properties in the Metropolitan Borough of Solihull. These properties are subject to a regular and high turnover of residents, which can lead to damage and loss of equipment. We therefore require a supplier of furniture to provide us with the necessary items to restock temporary accommodation properties and occasionally, transport furniture from one property to another.
      
      Solihull Metropolitan Borough Council has recently built a multi-occupancy accommodation unit at Ipswich Walk in the north of the borough. This unit has already been stocked under a separate contractual arrangement; however the subsequent replacement of furniture items as required is expected to be covered by this supply contract. 
      
      Please note that the supply of these goods will be of a responsive, ad-hoc nature and therefore we cannot guarantee a specific volume or value of orders. 
      
      The Contract is due to commence on 1 November 2017 for a period of one year with an option to extend for a further four 12 month periods subject to satisfactory performance and mutual agreement.
      
      It is the Employer's intention to appoint one supplier under this Contract. 
      
      Minimum Requirements
      
      ? All tenderers must be able to demonstrate experience in supplying goods to a similar housing department or function where the focus is on temporary accommodation. 
      
      ? Suppliers must also be able to meet a requirement to deliver on a next day basis from the date the order is received. 
      
      
      The successful contractor is to be selected through a formal tender process.
      
      In order to be considered for the award of the contract, suppliers must express an interest in this tender and complete the enclosed tender documents by no later than 12:00 midday on Friday 13th October 2017.

Additional information: 
This contract will be tendered through an electronic tendering portal at visit www.csw-jets.co.uk. Organisations will not be able to access documents unless they are registered on this portal. 

All documents can be downloaded from and submitted via the portal. 

The deadline date for submission of tenders is 12:00 midday on Friday 13th October 2017.

column62: - Research to define metrics for measuring progress in surface water flood risk management
column63:
The Adaptation Sub-Committee (ASC) of the Committee on Climate Change (CCC) is the government's statutory advisers on preparing for climate change. One of the roles of the ASC is to scrutinise progress made by the government in managing climate change risks. The Committee makes use of evidence to assess whether the government is delivering its own objectives, and whether these objectives are in-line with managing the long-term changes in risk.

The UK Climate Change Risk Assessment 2017 found that rainfall patterns in the UK are intensifying, with the existing drainage and public sewerage network already under severe pressure in some areas. However, there is currently no government objective for managing this risk in the long term, and the overall impact of ongoing actions from local authorities and water companies is unknown.

The ASC would like to define metrics to measure progress made in managing surface flooding at the local level, based on available data, and collate these metrics to gain a national picture of the current situation.
*** Please specification for more information ***

Additional information: Bids should be sent in time in time for receipt by 5pm on 18th October 2017

column62: Pool Farm construction of by-pass channels
column63:
Pool Farm Minewater Treatment Scheme is an existing MwTS located approximately 1km west of Auchengray, South Lanarkshire. (Grid Reference: NS 986 541).

The site is accessed off several minor roads from the Auchengray Road to Pool Farm and then via shared farm access tracks. The Coal Authority has rights of access to the scheme over the farm access tracks from Pool Farm.

We require a permanent bypass channel installing to allow the maintenance of reed bed 2 this year. This needs to give the flexibility to take the reed bed off-line as required, so control by penstocks or stop-logs will be required.

A blocked-off connection shall be incorporated, to facilitate a future connection to the inlet structure. (This will then form a second partial bypass, allowing reed bed 1 to be taken off-line for maintenance).

You are invited to submit a tender for providing the Authority with this requirement.

column62: HeadStart Kernow Youth Facilitators
column63:
Cornwall is one of six areas across England funded by the Big Lottery Fund to deliver its HeadStart Programme which brings together partnerships of young people, charities, health, parents, teachers and local authorities to help 10-16 year olds feel they have support in school, the community and at home, as well as tackling the stigma associated with mental health. The HeadStart Kernow Partnership has been awarded funding until 2021 to deliver an ambitious investment programme that enables a universal approach to promoting emotional resilience and mental wellbeing.  The HeadStart Kernow Vision, which has been co-produced with young people is:

'The emotional wellbeing and mental health of all children and young people is improved because they can easily access the right support when they need it'.

The Council is seeking to appoint a Service Provider who will be required to apply learning gained by the Programme to date and provide a delivery model to work with young people aged 10-16 years that will:

•	Offer direct provision of 1-1 and group support for young people to improve the quality of their emotional health and well- being.
•	Build the capacity of schools and community based organisations to support young people's emotional health and well-being. 
The Council welcomes a partnership and innovative approach to provision across Cornwall and involves young people in all aspects of design, delivery and evaluation.
This Contract Notice for 'HeadStart Kernow Youth Facilitators' (Reference DN297929) links to the Prior Information Notice (PIN Notice) published on Supply In The South West on 17 July 2017 (Reference DN288054) and as published in the Official Journal of the European Union on (OJEU) on 15 July 2017 (Reference 2017/S 134-274464)

column62: ENHANCING UK-CHINA BILATERAL TRADE AND INVESTMENT
column63:
The 2015 Strategic Defence and Security Review announced the establishment of the cross-government Prosperity Fund from 2016 to 2021. The Fund aims to promote inclusive economic growth and development and enhance the UK's bilateral trade and investment with partners.

In 2015 UK goods exports to China amounted to £13.1bn and services exports to China amounted to £3.7bn, i.e. China was the 5th and 14th largest destination for the UK's goods and services exports, respectively. The stock of Foreign Direct Investment from the UK to China was £9.7bn in 2015, up 5% from 2014, and the stock of Foreign Direct Investment from China to the UK totalled £1.8 billion in 2015, a 68% increase from 2014. This all adds up to a huge opportunity for UK business.

The proposed projects (policy proposals to remove market access barriers; analysis and policy development in relation to UK-China investment flows and access; and the assessment of possible UK-China development zone models) will help prepare the way for the UK-China trade relationship in the 2020s.

Additional information: 
https://fco.bravosolution.co.uk

column62: GP Direct Access Pathology for NHS Hounslow CCG
column63:
NHS Hounslow Clinical Commissioning Group (CCG) is commissioning an end to end pathology test service to Hounslow GPs. 
The CCG is seeking to benefit from a safe, reliable, quality assured and timely GP Direct Access Pathology Service that meets the needs of NHS Hounslow GP's and patients. 
The service must be flexible to accommodate future GP practice opening hours, support GPs to request tests effectively, facilitate sharing of patients acute and primary care test results and lastly take on board new test developments where they are affordable and deliver value to the whole patient pathway.  
Key commercial features of the contract will be a flexible pay per reportable test pricing mechanism along with marginal test pricing and incentivised demand management initiatives. The CCG requires a service which meets UKAS ISO15189 quality standards and deliver test results to stated Turnaround Times.
The contract to be offered as a result of this procurement exercise will be for an initial five year term commencing from 1st April 2018, with the option of an additional extension of up to three years.
Further information on the service is contained in the ITT Documentation.

Additional information: Organisations interested in tendering for this opportunity should visit the EU Supply at http://nhssbs.eu-supply.com and search for tender ID 29219. The ITT submission deadline is Noon on 25th October 2017.

There will be a Bidder Briefing Event to take place on Wednesday 4th October 2017. The briefing will take place from 10.00 to 11.30. The briefing will be held at Room 4W18, 4th Floor, Heart of Hounslow Centre for Health, 92 Bath Road, Hounslow, TW3 3EL.

column62: AHDB Foodservice Purchase Data Requirements
column63:
AHDB currently source Foodservice data through a Third party. The data monitors protein performance across the UK Foodservice industry. Access to this data allows AHDB to analyse the sector and the channels that make up Foodservice and monitor the performance of key sector-related products. The information is used, by AHDB to inform the industry on the latest trends and look at potential implications for AHDB sector-related products. The information is used at business meetings/presentations and also in the media in response to requests for market information/commentary.
This opportunity is in 2 Lots. Lot 1) Proposal to best meet AHDB 'Core requirements' specification within a budget of £48k per annum - clearly identifying any elements of the specification not included along with associated costs.
Lot 2) Proposal to best meet elements of AHDB 'Additional requirements' specification - clearly identifying any elements of the specification not included. No budget has been allocated.
For Lot 2 AHDB are at this stage looking for an outline of how an agency propose to get to the measures required, in particular the volume estimate read. 
Note: Suppliers can tender for both, Lots 1 & 2 or just either one of the two

column62: Modular Retail Pods for Stations
column63:
An opportunity has been identified to site a number of modular retail pods on various TfL and Crossrail premises and stations. These will not only allow us to provide exciting new retail opportunities for our customers, but also generate enhanced revenue to support investment in London's transport network. We anticipate these pods will mainly be occupied by A1, A3 and A5 tenants such as coffee bars, sandwich / snack retailers, confectionary outlets, newsagents and card retailers. TfL will be providing a steel / glass envelope with appropriate incoming services for tenants to fit out to suit their requirements. Tenant fit out will include the necessary fabric to support their business, but also services which could potentially include three phase power, HVAC and plumbing / drainage. 

TfL has procured a concept design for the pods which is detailed within this enquiry. We are seeking a supply chain to develop this design and then manufacture and install the units. There will also be an ongoing requirement for the provision of spare parts in the event of accidents, vandalism or other damage. 

Units are of steel and glass construction and are modular to allow various dimensional options as well as facilitating rapid installation and the possibility of straightforward location moves.

Additional information: Please complete and return the accompanying short questionnaire if you would be interested in taking part in this opportunity. 

The closing date for receipt of expressions of interest will be 17:00 on Thursday 5 October. Please send your responses by email to Benjamin Kennedy at benjaminkennedy@tfl.gov.uk. 

Following receipt of your expressions of interest, we may ask you to join us at our offices for a 1:1 engagement session about the opportunity. In your response, please also indicate whether you would be interested in participating in this engagement exercise. 

We look forward to your responses. Please feel free to contact me if you have any questions in the meantime. 

Contact details:
Benjamin Kennedy,
benjaminkennedy@tfl.gov.uk,
020 3054 7327,
07515 501040.

column62: Provision of a Recruitment Service
column63:
The Authority is looking to appoint a Potential Provider with the ability to identify high calibre candidates from the private sector who would be prepared to move to these challenging public sector roles should the current incumbent staff move on. The firm should have a proven background in Financial Institution Group recruitment and provide a report detailing candidates for the three positions as well as having approached the possible candidates to gauge levels of interest. The three roles are detailed on the attached description.

How to apply Instructions to Potential Providers: 

Potential Providers must first be registered on the Crown Commercial Service e-Sourcing Suite in order to respond to the Procurement. If you have not yet registered on the e-Sourcing Suite, this can be done online at https://gpsesourcing.cabinetoffice.gov.uk by following the link 'Register for CCS e-Sourcing'. 

Please note that, to register, you must have a valid DUNS number (as provided by Dun and Bradstreet) for the organisation which you are registering, who will be entering into a contract if invited to do so at the Invitation to Tender stage. Potential Providers should note that it could take up to 10 working days to obtain a DUNS number. 
Full instructions for registration and use of the system can be found at: 
http://gps.cabinetoffice.gov.uk/i-am-supplier/respond-tender 

Once you have registered on the e-Sourcing Suite, you will need to express your interest by emailing ExpressionOfInterest@Crowncommercial.gov.uk. The dead line for expressing an interest in the Request for Information event is Monday 9th October 2017 at 13:00.

Your email must clearly state: 
- name/reference of this procurement 
- the name of the registered supplier; and 
- the name and contact details 

Crown Commercial Service will then process your registration and assign your organisation to the opportunity. The registered user will receive a notification email to alert them once this has been done. 

It is advised however that Potential Providers register as soon as practically possible in order to receive the Invitation to Tender and have a sufficient amount of time to respond. Crown Commercial Service is not able to offer any extensions to the advertised procurement timetable. 

For technical assistance on use of the e-Sourcing Suite please contact the 
Helpdesk: 
Freephone: 0345 010 3503


Update: 26th September 2017 - The registration for interested has been extended until the Monday 9th October 2017. Please note that Suppliers MUST be set up on the portal by Wednesday 11th October 2017 for the tender to commence.
